normalization_record.normalized_question_text:
In a basketball shot, a student throws the basketball upward at an angle. A simplified diagram of the trajectory is shown in Figure B. The initial velocity has magnitude $v_{1}=5\mathrm{m}/\mathrm{s}$ and makes an angle $\theta=53^{\circ}$ with the vertical. The basketball hits the backboard directly above the basket, is reflected, and then falls through the center of the basket. The vertical distance between the impact point and the basket is $h=0.2\mathrm{m}$, the contact time with the backboard is $\Delta t=0.01\mathrm{s}$, the horizontal distance between the center of the basket and the backboard is $L=0.6\mathrm{m}$, the mass of the basketball is $m=0.6\mathrm{kg}$, and the gravitational acceleration is $g=10\mathrm{m}/\mathrm{s}^{2}$. Given $\sin53^{\circ}=0.8$ and $\cos53^{\circ}=0.6$, neglect air resistance and treat the basketball as a point mass.

Find:
1. the magnitude of the work $W$ done by the student on the basketball at the instant it is thrown;
2. the magnitudes of the velocity $v_{2}$ just before the basketball collides with the backboard and the velocity $v_{3}$ just after the collision;
3. the magnitude of the average horizontal impact force $F$ on the basketball during the collision with the backboard.

